### Drill 1: Basics of Background Work
# This request enqueues a fake email job in an in-memory queue.
POST http://localhost:3000/email
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "to": "user@example.com",
    "subject": "Hello Drill 1",
    "body": "This is enqueued in-memory."
}

### Drill 2: Worker Threads (Main Thread)
# This blocks the event loop with a heavy CPU calculation (Fibonacci).
GET http://localhost:3001/fib-main/40

### Drill 2: Worker Threads (Worker Thread)
# This runs the same calculation in a separate thread, keeping the event loop responsive.
GET http://localhost:3001/fib-worker/40

### Drill 3 & 4: Job Queues with Redis & BullMQ
# Enqueues a job into Redis using BullMQ for persistence and reliability.
POST http://localhost:3002/email
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "to": "user@example.com",
    "subject": "Hello BullMQ",
    "body": "Enqueued with persistence."
}

### Drill 3 & 4: Simulate Failure & Automatic Retries
# Passing "simulateFailure": true will cause the worker to fail twice before succeeding.
POST http://localhost:3002/email
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "to": "user@example.com",
    "subject": "Retry Test",
    "body": "This should fail twice and succeed on the third attempt.",
    "simulateFailure": true
}

### Drill 4: Idempotency Logic
# Multiple requests with the same "idempotencyKey" will result in only one unique job in the queue.
POST http://localhost:3002/email
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "idempotencyKey": "unique-msg-id-123",
    "to": "user@example.com",
    "subject": "Idempotent Msg",
    "body": "Sending this twice should result in a single job."
}

### Drill 4: Bull Board UI
# Visit this URL in your browser to inspect the state of the BullMQ queues.
GET http://localhost:3002/admin/queues
